Sleep interacts reciprocally with the gut microbiota. However, mechanisms of the gut microbe-brain metabolic axis that are
responsible for sleep behavior have remained largely unknown. Here, we showed that the absence of the gut microbiota can alter
sleep behavior. Sleep deprivation reduced butyrate levels in fecal content and the hypothalamus in speciﬁc pathogen-free mice but
not in germ-free mice. The microbial metabolite butyrate can promote sleep by modulating orexin neuronal activity in the lateral
hypothalamic area in mice. Insomnia patients had lower serum butyrate levels and a deﬁciency in butyrate-producing species
within the gut microbiota. Transplantation of the gut microbiota from insomnia patients to germ-free mice conferred insomnia-like
behaviors, accompanied by a decrease in serum butyrate levels. The oral administration of butyrate rescued sleep disturbances in
recipient mice. Overall, these ﬁndings reveal the causal role of microbial metabolic pathways in modulating insomnia-like
behaviors, suggesting potential therapeutic strategies for treating sleep disorders.
Molecular Psychiatry; https://doi.org/10.1038/s41380-024-02867-0
INTRODUCTION
Sleep is a crucial and complex physiological process of the body,
and its underlying mechanisms are gradually being revealed.
Notably, sleep can manifest in a brain-independent manner,
supported by the observation of sleep-like behavior in cnidarians
and Hydra vulgaris that lack a central nervous system [1, 2]. Thus,
signals from peripheral tissues can play a key role in sleep
regulation. Recent studies showed that dietary proteins can
activate cells in the ﬂy gut and then suppress arousal from sleep
[3]. Depletion of the gut microbiota by antibiotic administration
led to an increase in non-rapid eye movement (NREM) sleep
during the dark phase and a decrease during the light phase in
mice [4]. However, remaining elusive is how peripheral signaling
that is driven by gut microbes modulates sleep.
The gut microbiota can interact with brain function through the
microbial-gut-brain axis [5]. Gut bacterium–derived metabolites
can impact various physiological processes and behaviors in the
host and participate in the regulation of certain pathological
conditions, such as anxiety-like behavior [6] and autism-like
phenotypes
[7].
For
example,
the
microbial
metabolite
4-ethylphenyl sulfate promoted anxiety-like behavior in mice [6],
and the gut-produced microbial metabolite 5-aminovaleric acid
reduced neuronal excitability in the prefrontal cortex in BTBR mice
[7]. Additionally, some clinical studies reported signiﬁcant altera-
tions of diversity and composition of the gut microbiota in
individuals with chronic insomnia [8, 9]. In our previous clinical
and animal studies, we also found that sleep deprivation (SD)
signiﬁcantly altered gut microbiota functionality and metabolite
proﬁles. Short-chain fatty acids (SCFAs) played a pivotal role in
facilitating bidirectional communication between the gut and
brain [10, 11]. Additionally, recent research demonstrated that
SCFAs alleviated SD-induced cognitive dysfunction by regulating
inﬂammatory responses in mice [12]. Although some studies
reported the inﬂuence of the gut microbiota on the pathogenesis
of sleep disorders, the precise mechanisms by which the gut
microbiota modulates sleep-wake behaviors and how an aberrant
microbiota contributes to sleep disorders remain elusive.
In the present study, we sought to elucidate how the gut
microbiota shapes sleep behavior. We initially found changes in
sleep architecture and sleep homeostasis in germ-free (GF) mice.
We also found that butyrate, a metabolite that derives from the
gut microbiota, promoted sleep by inhibiting orexin neuronal
activity
in
the
lateral
hypothalamus
(LH).
Additionally,
we
characterized
the
gut
microbiome
and
butyrate
metabolic
