patterns in individuals with insomnia. We found that perturbations
of the intestinal gut microbiota contributed to the complex
pathogenesis of insomnia. Finally, oral butyrate administration
delayed the onset of sleep disturbances in recipient mice.
Altogether, our results revealed a gut microbe-brain metabolic
axis that underlies insomnia-like behaviors.
RESULTS
Gut microbiota affects sleep behaviors
To understand the role of the gut microbiota in regulating sleep-
wake behaviors, we recorded 24-h ambulatory electroencephalo-
gram (EEG)-electromyogram (EMG) in both speciﬁc pathogen-free
(SPF) and GF mice (Fig. 1A–C). Strikingly, EEG-EMG recordings
showed that the absence of the gut microbiota changed sleep-
wake architecture during both the light and dark phases. GF mice
exhibited a 10.45% decrease in the time of wakefulness during the
12-h light phase and a 10.36% increase in the time of wakefulness
during the 12-h dark phase compared with SPF mice (Fig. 1D).
Additionally, GF mice exhibited a 17.19% decrease in the time of
NREM sleep during the 12-h dark phase (Fig. 1E), along with an
18.20% increase in the time of REM sleep during the 12-h light
phase (Fig. 1F). No signiﬁcant differences in the 24-h time spent in
wakefulness or sleep were found. The sleep-wake architecture
analysis revealed a decrease in occurrence numbers of wakeful-
ness during the light and dark phases and an increase in the
episode duration of wakefulness in GF mice during the dark phase
(Supplementary Fig. 1A, B). GF mice also exhibited a decrease in
the number of occurrences of NREM sleep during the light and
dark phases and an increase in the episode duration of NREM
sleep during the light phase (Supplementary Fig. 1C, D). Addi-
tionally, GF mice exhibited a decrease in anxiety-like behavior
(Supplementary Fig. 2A–C), which is consistent with previous data
[13]. These ﬁndings demonstrated that the gut microbiota was
required for the maintenance of NREM sleep under physiological
conditions.
One question arises about whether changes in sleep-wake
architecture in GF mice are attributable to alterations of sleep
homeostasis. We performed a SD experiment, in which GF mice
were kept in wakefulness by gentle handling in their home cages
for 6 h starting at light onset (Fig. 1G). After SD, there is usually a
rebound in lost NREM sleep, a process termed sleep homeostasis.
Subsequently, sleep recovery was measured during the next 18 h.
Surprisingly, GF mice spent less time in sleep recovery after 6 h of
continuous SD (Fig. 1H, I). Furthermore, we analyzed the sleep-
wake cycle every 6 h after SD to examine whether the mice were
able to compensate for their lost sleep during the baseline period.
We found that sleep recovery occurred mostly during the dark
phase following SD. Although both SPF and GF mice exhibited
subsequent sleep recovery (Supplementary Fig. 3A–F), GF mice
that were subjected to SD (GF-SD mice) exhibited 21.45% and
21.26% increases in wakefulness during Zeitgeber time (ZT) 12-18
and ZT 18-24, respectively, compared with SPF-SD mice (Fig. 1J).
The increase in wakefulness occurred concomitantly with the
reduction of NREM sleep, with 19.57% and 18.60% decreases
during ZT 12-18 and ZT 18-24, respectively (Fig. 1K). There was no
signiﬁcant change in REM sleep (Fig. 1L). Altogether, these results
suggest that the absence of the gut microbiota alters sleep
homeostasis in mice.
Gut microbiome-derived butyrate modulates sleep behavior
Neuronal function in the brain can be regulated by microbial
small-molecule metabolites [7, 14]. We postulated that alterations
of metabolic processes may underlie the regulation of sleep
homeostasis that is mediated by the microbiome. To identify
speciﬁc metabolites that are involved in gut microbiota-mediated
sleep-related behavioral changes, We conducted targeted meta-
bolomics on fecal content and hypothalamus tissue samples from
SPF, GF, and SD groups of mice (Fig. 2A). The hypothalamus plays
a pivotal role in sleep-wake regulation [15], with a notable
interaction with the gut microbiota [16]. A total of 237 metabolites
were detected in the fecal content, and 191 metabolites were
identiﬁed in the brain (Supplementary Fig. 4A–D). Among these,
39 and 61 metabolites in the fecal content and hypothalamus
tissue, respectively, exhibited differential regulation after SD in SPF
mice (Fig. 2B, C). Speciﬁcally, we utilized GF animals to exclude
metabolites that show differences in the hypothalamus and fecal
content after SD. This approach allowed us to focus on the
metabolites that exhibited differential expression in the hypotha-
lamus and fecal content of SPF mice following SD. Consequently,
we identiﬁed metabolites produced by gut microbiota that may
be associated with sleep regulation.
Excluding the differentially changed metabolites following SD in
both fecal content and the hypothalamus in GF mice, only three
potential metabolites exhibited differential changes between SPF
and
SPF-SD
mice:
butyrate,
phenylacetic
acid,
and
10Z-
heptadecenoic acid (Fig. 2D). Speciﬁcally, after SD, only butyrate
decreased in both the fecal content, and hypothalamus tissue in
SPF mice, and this decrease was markedly blocked in GF mice
(Fig. 2E, F and Supplementary Fig 4E–H). We also measured the
serum levels of butyrate, and the results were consistent with the
ﬁndings mentioned above (Supplementary Fig. 5).
To further verify whether butyrate affects sleep behaviors, we
implanted EEG and EMG electrodes to record sleep-wake states
following the oral administration of tributyrin, a precursor of
butyrate [17]. Tributyrin provides a more controlled and sustained
release of butyrate, enhancing its effective absorption throughout
both the small and large intestinal epithelium. Additionally,
supplementation with tributyrin has been shown to increase
butyrate availability in the brain [18–20]. Since the light phase is
the relatively quiescent period for mice, during which they sleep
more, this could mask the sleep-promoting effects of butyrate.
Therefore, the butyrate intervention was performed during the
SPF mice’s active phase. Tributyrin was administered via oral
gavage at the onset of the dark phase, and the sleep-wake cycle
was measured during the subsequent 10 h period (Fig. 3A, B).
Tributyrin administration led to a signiﬁcant 39.50% reduction of
wakefulness during the post-administration period (Fig. 3C, F). The
decrease in wakefulness was accompanied by a signiﬁcant
100.05% increase in NREM sleep and a substantial 77.99% increase
in REM sleep (Fig. 3D–F). Furthermore, the sleep architecture
analysis revealed that the decrease in wakefulness time was
attributable to a signiﬁcant decrease in the mean duration of wake
episodes, and the increase in sleep time was attributable to a
signiﬁcant increase in the number of NREM and REM sleep
episodes in tributyrin-treated mice (Supplementary Fig. 6A–F).
However, our ﬁndings indicate that valeric acid does not have a
comparable effect on sleep, suggesting a unique role for butyrate
in sleep modulation (Supplementary Fig. 7). Overall, we found that
microbiome-derived butyrate can promote sleep in mice.
Butyrate precursor tributyrin reduces orexin neuron
activation in the lateral hypothalamus
Earlier studies showed a strong link between SCFAs and the
hypothalamus [21]. To further screen the speciﬁc brain region of
the hypothalamus that is involved in butyrate-mediated sleep-
wake behaviors, we conducted Fos expression mapping as a
proxy to examine neural activity after tributyrin administration in
mice [22]. Our ﬁndings showed a reduction of Fos signals in the
LH in tributyrin-treated mice compared with saline controls
(Supplementary Fig. 8A, B). Additionally, prominent labeling was
observed in the ventromedial hypothalamus (VMH), which mainly
modulates feeding behavior [23]. The activity of some brain
regions, including the paraventricular nucleus of hypothalamus
(PVN), dorsomedial hypothalamic nucleus (DMH), and supra-
mammillary nucleus (SuM), did not signiﬁcantly change after
