tributyrin treatment (Supplementary Fig. 8A, B). These ﬁndings
suggest that tributyrin can repress neural activity in the LH,
indicating that the LH may be a potential hub that modulates the
interaction between microbial metabolites and sleep. Neuronal
populations in the LH primarily consist of orexin and melanin-
concentrating hormone (MCH) neurons, which play a crucial role
in regulating sleep and wakefulness [24, 25]. Therefore, we
assessed neuronal activity in the LH using immunoﬂuorescent
staining for Fos and orexin A or MCH. There was a signiﬁcant
decrease in the number of activated orexin A neurons in
tributyrin-treated mice compared with saline controls (Fig. 3G, H).
Fos expression in MCH neurons was not signiﬁcantly different
between the two groups (Fig. 3I, J).
To directly measure the intrinsic activity of orexin neurons in
response to the butyrate precursor tributyrin, we monitored the
activity of LHOx neurons in mice by measuring Ca2+ transients
during natural sleep/wake transitions using ﬁber photometry
(Fig. 4A, B). LHOx neuronal activity during wakefulness was
signiﬁcantly higher than during NREM sleep (Fig. 4C). LHOx neuron
activity signiﬁcantly changed during natural sleep/wake transi-
tions (Fig. 4D, E). The frequency of orexin neuron transients in
NREM states was signiﬁcantly lower in tributyrin-treated mice
(Fig. 4F). These results suggest that tributyrin promotes sleep
possibly by inhibiting LH orexin neurons.
To examine the effect of tributyrin on the neuronal excitability
of LHOx neurons, we employed a patch clamp and observed a
