Gut microbiota composition and microbial butyrate
metabolism are altered in insomnia patients
The above ﬁndings demonstrated that the absence of the gut
microbiota can inﬂuence sleep behavior via a metabolic pathway.
Next, we sought to determine whether insomnia patients exhibit
disturbances of gut microbiota composition and impairments in
microbial butyrate metabolism. Fecal samples were obtained from
patients with insomnia and healthy controls, enabling the
characterization
of
gut
microbial
composition
by
shotgun
metagenomic sequencing. Our results showed that insomnia
patients exhibited lower α diversity (Chao1 Index, Simpson Index,
Shannon index) in the microbiota compared with the healthy
control group (Fig. 5A). Additionally, β diversity did not differ
between insomnia patients and healthy controls (Supplementary
Fig. 10A). The genus-level information of gut microbiota is
provided in Supplementary Table 2. Across the dataset, Bacter-
oides was the most abundant genus in both insomnia patients and
healthy controls (Fig. 5B and Supplementary Fig. 10B). Compared
with healthy controls, lower-abundance genera in insomnia
patients included Odoribacter, Megamonas, Lachnospira, Entero-
bacter, Oscillibacter, and Dysosmobacter. To determine whether
there are abnormalities in the intestinal ﬂora of microbial butyrate
metabolism in insomnia patients, we measured the abundance of
butyrate producers. Based on previous studies [26], we observed
the abundance of butyrate producers in our samples. A signiﬁcant
decrease in 39 butyrate producers was observed in insomnia
patients compared with a decrease in only one butyrate producer
in the control group, indicating a diminished butyrate-producing
microbiome in the gut in insomnia patients (Fig. 5C).
Polysomnography (PSG) is a gold standard to objectively
measure sleep [27]. We next tested correlations between butyrate
producers and PSG indicators. Correlation-based analysis of the
paired
microbiome–PSG
dataset
revealed
that
19
butyrate
producers signiﬁcantly correlated with PSG (Fig. 5D). To conﬁrm
the importance of the gut microbiota in modulating microbial
butyrate metabolism, we performed targeted SCFA metabolomics
analysis to quantitatively determine SCFAs in serum by gas
chromatography-mass spectrometry (GC-MS). Serum butyrate
levels signiﬁcantly decreased in insomnia patients compared with
healthy controls (Fig. 5E). These results indicate that disturbances
of the gut microbiome and butyrate metabolome are closely
related to insomnia.
Germ-free mice that receive microbiota from insomnia
patients exhibit sleep disturbances, which are recovered by
butyrate supplementation
Human studies of microbiota associations with sleep disorders are
well-documented, but experiments of causality are required to
further establish the involvement of the gut microbiota in sleep
disturbances. To elucidate causal relationships between gut
microbial alterations and sleep disturbances, we transplanted
fecal microbiota from healthy controls and insomnia patient
donors to GF mice (Fig. 6A). To validate the ﬁdelity of microbiota
transplantation, we collected feces from mice that were colonized
with human samples. The recipient mice were subjected to 16S
rRNA
gene
sequencing
at
3
weeks
post-fecal
microbiota
transplantation (FMT). As expected, FMT-insomnia (FMT_IN) mice
exhibited different bacterial proﬁles from FMT-healthy (FMT_HE)
mice (Supplementary Fig. 11A, B). Additionally, EEG and EMG
electrodes were implanted to record sleep-wake states after
3 weeks of FMT (Fig. 6B). The results showed that the total
amounts of each stage in the 24-h phase did not signiﬁcantly
change (Fig. 6C). Compared with FMT_HE mice, FMT_IN mice
exhibited a 26.17% increase in wakefulness in the 12-h light phase
and a 7.08% decrease in NREM sleep in the 12-h light phase
(Fig. 6D). No signiﬁcant change was found in each stage in the 12-
h dark phase (Fig. 6E). Furthermore, the sleep architecture analysis
revealed that the increases in wakefulness time were attributable
to signiﬁcantly longer wakefulness episodes in FMT_IN mice
(Supplementary Fig. 12). No difference in anxiety-like behavior was
observed in FMT_HE or FMT_IN mice (Supplementary Fig. 13).
Collectively, these ﬁndings suggest that colonization with micro-
biota from insomnia patients is sufﬁcient to induce insomnia-like
behaviors.
To further investigate the underpinnings of the role of the gut
microbiota in sleep disturbances, we tested whether microbiota
from insomnia patients can impact serum butyrate levels in mice.
Consistent with the human results, we found that serum butyrate
levels were signiﬁcantly lower in FMT_IN mice (Fig. 6F), indicating
that disturbances of microbial butyrate metabolism are sufﬁcient
to decrease circulating butyrate levels. Next, we assessed Fos
signals of LHOx neurons to screen their activity during microbiota-
mediated sleep disturbances. There was a signiﬁcant increase in
the number of activated LHOx neurons in FMT_IN mice compared
with their respective control groups (Fig. 6G, H). These ﬁndings
suggest that the human microbiota can modulate sleep-wake
behaviors
in
mice
through
the
production
of
neuroactive
microbial metabolites, such as butyrate, potentially involving the
regulation of LHOx neuron activity.
Considering the lower levels of butyrate in FMT-recipient mice,
we hypothesized that this metabolite in the gut might play a role
in recovering insomnia-like behaviors. By orally administering
sodium butyrate in FMT_IN mice for 3 weeks (Fig. 7A), we found
that sodium butyrate improved the sleep disturbance phenotype
in FMT_IN mice during the 12-h light phase (Fig. 7B). Notably,
systemic sodium butyrate administration resulted in a signiﬁcant
13.27% decrease in wakefulness and 7.71% increase in NREM
sleep in the 12-h light phase (Fig. 7C, D). Mice treated with sodium
butyrate displayed distinct bacterial proﬁles compared to the
control group, indicating that butyrate administration inﬂuences
gut microbiota composition. (Supplementary Fig. 14). Further-
more, the EEG spectral activity results showed that sodium
butyrate decreased the theta band and increased the beta band
power during wakefulness (Fig. 7F). It also decreased the delta
band and increased the theta band power during NREM sleep
(Fig. 7G), along with a decrease in the theta band during REM
sleep (Fig. 7H). These results suggest that sodium butyrate
administration can rescue insomnia-like behaviors in mice.
DISCUSSION
Studies of neural circuits have demonstrated the profound
signiﬁcance of global brain activity in regulating sleep-wake
behavior [28]. However, the role of peripheral intestinal signals in
sleep regulation should not be overlooked. The present ﬁndings
indicated a crucial role for the gut microbiota and its microbial
metabolite butyrate in maintaining an optimal sleep-wake balance
(Fig. 8). We found that gut microbiota depletion decreased the
nocturnal
sleep
duration.
Surprisingly,
introducing
the
gut
microbiota from patients with insomnia into rodents induced
sleep disturbances that were similar to insomnia patients.
Furthermore, we found that butyrate, a microbial-derived meta-
bolic byproduct, functioned as a pivotal gut-brain axis signal
transducer in sleep regulation through the modulation of orexin
signaling in the LH. Disruptions of intestinal butyrate biosynthesis
that are caused by perturbations of the gut microbiota can
potentially lead to sleep disturbances by altering the dynamics of
LH orexin neurons. Importantly, supplementation with butyrate
alleviated sleep disturbances that were induced by disruptions of
the gut microbiota, highlighting its potential implications as a
therapeutic intervention to mitigate sleep disorders.
