Molecular Psychiatry
Previous studies demonstrated that absence of the gut
microbiota can induce a wide range of behavioral changes,
including
a
low
anxiety-like
behavioral
phenotype
[13],
depression-like behavior [29], and alterations of the fear response
[30]. Absence of the gut microbiota can affect sleep rebound in
Drosophila [31], but no study has reported any alterations of sleep
characteristics in GF mice, which are a powerful model for
studying the role of microbiota in gut-brain communication [32].
In the present study, we found that absence of the gut microbiota
disrupted sleep-wake patterns and sleep homeostasis in mice.
Speciﬁcally, GF mice required shorter sleep recovery after SD.
Consistent with our ﬁndings, recent studies showed that axenic
ﬂies exhibited a reduction of sleep rebound following SD [31].
Furthermore, to investigate the potential impact of intestinal ﬂora
imbalances on sleep disturbances, we conducted gut microbiota
transplantation from insomnia patients to GF mice. Recipient mice
that
received
microbiota
from
insomnia
patients
exhibited
disruptions of sleep patterns, indicating a signiﬁcant inﬂuence of
the gut microbiota on sleep-wake behavior. Prior research has
indicated that SPF male and female mice exhibit distinct
responses to SD. Speciﬁcally, males tend to experience a more
signiﬁcant increase in both NREM and REM sleep following SD,
while females show a relatively modest increase [33]. These
observations underscore the necessity of treating sex as a critical
biological variable in our experiments, given that males and
females may react differently to sleep disruptions and related
interventions, including those concerning gut microbiota and the
gut-brain axis. Further investigation is essential to elucidate the
underlying mechanisms driving these differences.
The modulation of host behavior by the gut microbiota occurs
through diverse pathways, a crucial mechanism of which is the
production of neuroactive small molecules [34]. Microbiome-
derived metabolites, such as SCFAs, bile acids, indole derivatives,
and some amino acids, play a critical role in the etiology and
pathogenesis of brain disorders [35, 36]. SCFAs are the major end-
products of microbial fermentation, which are able to translocate
from the intestine to the systemic circulation and cross the blood-
brain barrier [37]. Our metagenomic study indicated that butyrate
producers decreased in insomnia patients. This result is consistent
with a prior study that reported that patients with chronic
insomnia exhibited a decrease in the abundance of these butyrate
producers [8]. Intestinimonas butyriciproducens, which showed a
lower relative abundance in our insomnia samples, has been
reported to produce butyrate and was also decreased in autism-
spectrum disorder [38]. Considering the composition complexity
of intestinal microecology under real pathophysiological condi-
tions, a reasonable proposition is that the composition of these
micro-ecological differences may ultimately dictate interindividual
differences in sleep. The ways in which the co-existing gut
microbiota interactively regulates host signaling pathways and
