Z. Wang et al.
9
Molecular Psychiatry
behavioral phenotypes are an intriguing issue for future studies.
Furthermore, we found that transplantation of the gut microbiota
from insomnia patients to GF mice led to insomnia-like behavioral
features, accompanied by a decrease in butyrate levels. Moreover,
our previous study found that transplantation of the gut
microbiota from SD-exposed humans to GF mice induced
cognitive impairments, accompanied by a decrease in butyrate
levels [10]. These ﬁndings support the pivotal role of the gut
microbiota in sleep disturbances and the dysregulation of
butyrate homeostasis.
We found that oral tributyrin administration promoted NREM
sleep in mice. Tributyrin is digested and absorbed in the upper
intestine and then transported to the blood circulation [39], ﬁnally
increasing plasma butyrate levels. Tributyrin allows for a more
controlled and sustained release of butyrate, ensuring effective
absorption across both the small and large intestinal epithelium.
Butyrate is known to be involved in a range of behavioral
regulations, and previous research highlights its signiﬁcant role in
modulating mood and cognition [40]. Numerous studies have
consistently reported beneﬁcial effects of butyrate treatment in
various brain disorders [41, 42]. Notably, butyrate administration
can promote sleep in animals [43] but effectively ameliorate
neuroinﬂammation and cognitive impairments in SD mice [44].
Consistent with these ﬁndings, the present study highlighted the
potential of providing butyrate supplementation for 3 weeks to
improve insomnia-like behavior in FMT_IN mice. Accordingly,
identifying gut microbiome-derived regenerative small molecules
could provide promising therapeutic possibilities for insomnia and
other sleep disorders.
The present study identiﬁed a hypothalamic region, the LH, that
speciﬁcally
controls
butyrate-induced
sleep
behavior.
The
hypothalamus coordinates various fundamental behaviors, such
as sleep, wakefulness, feeding, and motivated behaviors [45–47].
Previous studies reported that SCFAs may modulate levels of
neurotransmitters and neurotrophic factors [48]. Acute oral
butyrate administration suppressed the activity of orexigenic
neurons that express neuropeptide Y in the hypothalamus [49].
We also found a signiﬁcant decrease in the activity of orexin A
neurons in LH regions in tributyrin-treated mice. A large body of
evidence indicates that LHOx neurons play an important role in the
generation of wakefulness [50], and the dysfunction of LHOx
networks has been proposed to be related to the pathophysiology
of insomnia. Either orexin overexpression or orexin neuron
hyperactivity was shown to be involved in the pathology of
insomnia
[51].
Combined
with
our
ﬁndings
that
the
gut
microbiome can lead to the hyperactivity of orexin neurons in
FMT_IN mice, along with recent studies that demonstrated the
ability of the gut microbiome to modulate hypothalamic gene
expression [52, 53], it is plausible that the microbiome plays a
causal role in sleep disorders by disrupting hypothalamic neuron
homeostasis through perturbations of butyrate metabolism.
Multiple mechanisms may underlie the regulatory role of
butyrate in sleep. The vagus nerve serves as the primary high-
speed route for bidirectional communication between the CNS
and the enteric nervous system [54]. Indeed, previous studies have
shown that vagotomy does not prevent rebound sleep following
SD in rats, indicating that the vagus nerve may have a speciﬁc,
selective role in regulating sleep [55]. What’s more, butyrate can
