Z. Wang et al.
10
Molecular Psychiatry
activate the vagus nerve and hypothalamus by traversing the
blood-brain barrier (BBB) and binding to such receptors as G
protein-coupled receptors in both intestinal cells and the brain
[56, 57]. For example, GPR41 was found in rat cortex neurons, and
its expression was increased by butyrate administration, suggest-
ing that butyrate can regulate neuronal signaling in the brain [58].
Further research is necessary to uncover the intricate role of
butyrate in neurobiological processes, particularly in the gut-brain
neural circuit of sleep. Previous studies have shown that butyrate
can cross the BBB [59]. Recent studies have demonstrated that
tributyrin supplementation enhances brain butyrate availability
[20]. To explore this mechanism further, future research will
employ 14C-labeled butyrate or its precursors to trace radioactive
signals. This will allow us to examine whether butyrate affects the
hypothalamus through the circulatory system or via vagus nerve
signaling pathways. Orexin receptors, particularly OX1R, are
indeed widely distributed throughout the enteric nervous system
(ENS), suggesting a signiﬁcant role in gastrointestinal function
[60]. The localization of OX1R in nerve ﬁbers within the ganglia,
muscle, and mucosa is consistent with a presynaptic role of the
receptor, potentially modulating neurotransmitter release in these
regions. Given the interactions between the gut and brain,
particularly in the context of SD, changes in orexin receptor
expression or function could inﬂuence gastrointestinal processes
and alter gut microbiota composition. Orexin’s involvement in
both central and peripheral systems supports its potential role in
mediating gut-brain axis responses, especially under conditions
like SD that are known to affect both orexin signaling and gut
health.
In summary, we showed that the gut microbiota plays a role in
sleep via the microbial metabolite regulation of orexin signaling in
the LH. Our ﬁndings established a critical connection between
microbe metabolism and sleep behaviors, suggesting novel
microbiota (metabolite)-targeting interventions to manage insom-
nia and other sleep disorders.
MATERIALS AND METHODS
Human study
Patients with primary insomnia.
The patients were screened at Peking
University Sixth Hospital, Beijing, China. All participants were Han
Chinese and signed informed consent forms before participation. All of
the experimental procedures were conducted in accordance with the
Declaration of Helsinki and performed with adequate understanding and
written informed consent from the subjects. The study was approved by
the ethics committee of Peking University Sixth Hospital. The clinical trial
was registered in the Chinese Clinical Trial Registry (no. ChiCTR-ROC-
17012112). People with primary insomnia were diagnosed according to
the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, 5th edition. All
participants had not received any medication for at least 2 months prior
to the study and had a normal Body Mass Index (18.5-28.0 kg/m2).
Exclusion
criteria
included
(1)
obstructive
sleep
apnea
and
other comorbid sleep disorders, (2) presence of any physical disease,
including diseases of the digestive system (e.g., gastroesophageal reﬂux
disease, peptic ulcer, inﬂammatory bowel disease, functional gastro-
intestinal disease, chronic constipation or diarrhea, liver disease, tumors
of the digestive system), cardiovascular and cerebrovascular diseases,
endocrine and metabolic diseases, other chronic inﬂammatory diseases,
and bacterial, fungal, or viral infections in any part of the body,
(3) dementia and neurodevelopmental disorders, (4) current and lifetime
