Molecular Psychiatry
history of any psychiatric disorders, (5) shift work or travel across more
than one time zone in the past 6 months, (6) habitual drinking of
caffeine, tea, and liquor, (7) alcoholics and drug abusers, and (8) women
who were pregnant, menstruating, or breast feeding (female subjects
were asked to participate in the study 10 days before their menstrual
cycle began).
Healthy controls.
The healthy controls were recruited from the commu-
nity through advertisements. All participants signed informed consent
prior to participation. The study was approved by the ethics committee of
Peking University Sixth Hospital. The healthy controls reported regular
sleep-wake schedules for at least 6 months before participation in the
study. They followed a regular bedtime schedule (bedtime at 11:00
PM ± 30 min and waking time at 7:00 AM ± 30 min) to minimize any effects
of prior sleep loss on the results. All healthy controls were free from any
medical and psychiatric conditions and had a normal Body Mass Index
(18.5-25.0 kg/m2). The exclusion criteria were the following: (1) habitual
drinking of caffeine, tea, and liquor, (2) habitual cigarette use, (3) past or
current use of any medications within 2 months, and (4) shift work or travel
across more than one time zone in the past 6 months. Information about
each participant’s medical and psychiatric history was obtained in an initial
interview. Potential healthy controls who appeared to meet the inclusion
criteria proceeded through a sequence of in-depth screening procedures,
including the Structured Clinical Interview for Diagnostic and Statistical
Manual of Mental Disorders, 5th edition, disorders and a physical
examination. Detailed characteristics of these recruited subjects are shown
in Supplementary Table 1.
Mouse models
Male GF and SPF BALB/c mice were bred at the Department of Laboratory
Animal Science, Third Military Medical University, Chongqing, China. All of
the animals were housed under a 12 h/12 h light/dark cycle (lights on 7:00
AM to 7:00 PM) with controlled temperature (21-22°C) and humidity (55%
± 5%). Standard laboratory chow and water were provided ad libitum. The
animal experimentation protocols were reviewed and approved by the
local ethics committee of Third Military Medical University, Chongqing,
China. All experimental procedures conformed to guidelines and protocols
approved by the Animal Core Facility of Third Military Medical University
and followed the guidelines for the National Institute of Health Guide for
the Care and Use of Laboratory Animals. Our estimates of the number of
animals that were required for behavioral testing (n ≥6/group) and
immunoﬂuorescence (n ≥4/group) were based on our past experience in
the laboratory and previous research.
Methods details
Sleep deprivation in mice.
The SD methods in animals were described in
detail in our previous studies [10]. During the SD period, mice (7-8 weeks
old) were housed in cages in their home environment. To reduce the
animals’ stress, gentle handling was performed to keep the mice awake
[61, 62]. In the SD groups, the mice were physically handled or gently
touched once they began to close their eyes and recline. Mice in the
control group were allowed to sleep uninterrupted.
Virus injection
Mice were anesthetized with isoﬂurane (1-2%) and placed on a stereotaxic
apparatus (RWD Life Technology, Shenzhen, Guangzhou province, China).
The scalp was cut along the midline to expose the skull, and a cotton swab
was used to clean connective tissue on the skull surface. The skull was
adjusted under a microscope to ensure it was horizontal. Small holes were
drilled on the skull for virus injection. After carefully removing the dura, the
virus was injected into target brain regions. To speciﬁcally record the Ca2+
activity of orexin neurons, rAAV-hypocretin-GCaMp6s-WPRE-pA (BrainVTA
Technology, Wuhan, Hubei province, China) was injected in the LH (from
bregma:
anterior-posterior
[AP] = −1.35 mm;
medial-lateral
[ML]
=
0.95 mm; dorsal-ventral [DV] = 4.95 mm).
For
patch-clamp
recording,
AAV-hypocretin-EGFP-WPRE
(BrainVTA
Technology, Wuhan, Hubei province, China) was injected in the LH (from
bregma: AP = −1.35 mm; ML = ± 0.95 mm; DV = 4.95 mm). To chemogen-
etically activate orexin neurons, AAV-EF1α-DIO-hM3D(Gq)-mCherry and
AAV-hypocretin-CRE (BrainVTA Technology, Wuhan, Hubei province, China)
were injected in the LH (from bregma: AP = −1.35 mm; ML = ± 0.95 mm;
DV = 4.95 mm).
EEG/EMG recording and analysis
Polysomnographic recordings were performed using EEG/EMG electrodes
that were implanted over the mouse cortex. Two screws were afﬁxed in the
frontal region (from bregma, AP = +1.50 mm; ML = ± 1.50 mm), and two
screws were afﬁxed in the lateral parietal region (from bregma: AP = −3.5
mm; ML = +4.0 mm or −3.0 mm). Two electrode wires were directly
inserted in the neck musculature for EMG recording. The electrodes and
screws were ﬁxed to the skull with dental cement. The data acquisition
system (CerePlex Direct) received digital signals via ﬂexible cables at a
sampling rate of 500 Hz. EEG and EMG activities were ampliﬁed and ﬁltered
(EEG, motion acceleration, LFP: low pass 250 Hz, EMG: band-pass 10-
250 Hz) [63]. Following surgery, the mice were housed to recover for
7 days. All mice were habituated to the recording cages for 2-3 days before
starting the recordings. The polysomnographic recordings were auto-
matically scored ofﬂine every 4 s as wakefulness, NREM sleep, or REM sleep
using SleepSign 3.0, based on previously described validated criteria [64].
Sleep-wake stages were veriﬁed by an investigator who was blinded to
group assignment. To analyze the spectral activity of EEG signals, a series
of standardized procedures were employed. The raw EEG signals were ﬁrst
segmented into consecutive 4 s epochs. Each epoch was then subjected to
a Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) to convert the time-domain signals into the
frequency domain, speciﬁcally within the range of 0-30 Hz. Epochs that
contained high-amplitude movement artifacts were excluded from the
spectral analysis. The normalized EEG power was computed as the ratio of
the power within a speciﬁc frequency band to the total power across the
entire spectrum under analysis.
Fiber photometry recording and analysis
For photometry recording, an optical ﬁber was implanted above the LH
(from bregma: AP = −1.35 mm; ML = 0.95 mm; DV = 4.94 mm) 3-4 weeks
after the virus injection. Fiber Photometry System (RWD Life Science,
Shenzhen, Guangzhou province, China) equipped with the 470 and
410 nm excitation lasers. 470 nm laser excited GCaMP ﬂuorescence signals
for measuring the Ca2+ activity of LHOx neurons, and 410 nm laser was
used as the control channel. For the analysis of the Ca2+ activity of orexin
neurons in response to the butyrate precursor tributyrin, data were
collected during the active phase (ZT12-18) of the mice. The change of
Ca2+ signal was calculated from formula of ΔF/F = (F−F0)/F0. GCaMP6s
signals were staged to different behavioral state transitions based on the
simultaneously recorded EEG/EMG signals. Sleep-wake phase transition
state category includes NREM to wake and wake to NREM. During different
sleep/wakefulness states transitions, the time points of state transitions
were deﬁned as 0 time based on EEG/EMG activity. Peak analysis of the
signals was calculated by determining the median average deviation
(MAD) of the corrected/normalized data set and peaks were identiﬁed as
events that exceeded the MAD by 2.91 deviations.
Electrophysiological recording
The mice were deeply anesthetized with 2.0% isoﬂurane (RWD, Shenzhen,
China), and coronal brain slices (300 μm) were cut in a cutting solution that
contained 194 mM sucrose, 26 mM NaHCO3, 1.2 mM NaH2PO4, 4.5 mM KCl,
10 mM glucose, 30 mM NaCl, and 10 mM MgCl2 (pH 7.4, 315-320 mOsm)
using a Leica VT1200S vibratome. Brain slices were incubated in artiﬁcial
cerebrospinal ﬂuid (ACSF) solution that contained 124 mM NaCl, 4.5 mM
KCl, 26 mM NaHCO3, 1.2 mM NaH2PO4, 10 mM glucose, 2 mM CaCl2, and
1 mM MgCl2 (pH 7.4, 315-320 mOsm) for 30 min at 32 °C. The beaker that
contained the brain slices was then transferred to room temperature for
cooling and incubated for 30 min. Electrophysiological recordings were
performed in ACSF solution, which was incubated with mixed oxygen and
circulated into the recording chamber at a ﬂow rate of 2 mL/min. A
temperature control system was used to control the temperature of the
recording chamber at 28 °C to maintain neuronal activity. Target neurons
were visualized using an orthostatic infrared differential interference
contrast and ﬂuorescent microscope (BX51WI, Olympus). Recordings were
conducted in whole-cell mode using a MultiClamo700B ampliﬁer (Axon
CNS). Patch pipettes (5-7 MU) were pulled from borosilicate glass
capillaries (1.5 mm outer diameter; WPI) using a two-stage horizontal
puller (P-1000, Sutter Instruments). Pipettes were ﬁlled with an internal
solution that contained 120 mM CsCl, 10 mM EGTA, 10 mM HEPES, 4 mM
MgCl2, 2 mM Mg-ATP, and 0.5 mM Na-GTP (pH 7.3, 296 mOsm). Signals
were ﬁltered at 3 kHz and digitized at 10 kHz using Digidata 1440 A (Axon
CNS). Data with a series resistance (Rs) were monitored throughout the
experiments. Data with Rs > 25 MU or changes >20% were discarded
Z. Wang et al.
12
Molecular Psychiatry
before further analysis using Clampﬁt 10.5 (Molecular devices) and
Minianalysis (Synaptosoft).
Serum data
Human.
Venous blood was collected at 8:00 AM. The blood samples were
allowed to clot for 60 min at room temperature before centrifugation at
1000 × g for 15 min. The supernatant was transferred from the 5 ml
samples. The serum was then immediately removed and aliquoted. The
samples were stored at −80 °C until the assays.
Mice.
Trunk blood (1 ml, eyeball enucleation) was obtained at the end of
the study using heparin-coated tubes. The blood samples were allowed to
clot for 60 min at room temperature before centrifugation at 3000 × g for
10 min, and the samples were taken and stored at −80 °C.
Fecal sample collection, microbiota transfer experiments and
16S rRNA gene sequencing
Fecal samples were freshly collected from the subjects or FMT model. The
samples were immediately frozen after collection and stored at -80°C
before the analysis. The procedures for preparing the fecal samples were
described in a previous study, while the protocol for fecal microbiota
transplantation was based on our earlier research [10, 29]. The cecum was
harvested, snap-frozen, and stored at −80 °C before the analysis. DNA from
the fecal content was extracted using the Qiagen QIAmp Fast DNA Stool
Mini Kit (Qiagen, Valencia, CA, USA) coupled with an initial bead-beating
step as previously described [65]. DNA was quantiﬁed using a Qubit
Fluorometer with the Qubit dsDNA BR Assay kit (Invitrogen, Carlsbad, CA,
USA), and quality was checked by running an aliquot on 1% agarose gel.
Variable regions V3-V4 of the bacterial 16S rRNA gene were ampliﬁed
with degenerate polymerase chain reaction (PCR) primers: 341 F (5’-
ACTCCTACGGGAGGCAGCAG-3’)
and
806 R
(5’-GGACTACHVGGGTWTC-
TAAT-3’). Both forward and reverse primers were tagged with Illumina
adapter and pad and linker sequences. Polymerase chain reaction
enrichment was performed in a 50 μl reaction that contained 30 ng
template, fusion PCR primer, and PCR master mix. The PCR products were
puriﬁed with Ampure XP beads and eluted in elution buffer. Libraries were
qualiﬁed using an Agilent 2100 bioanalyzer (Agilent, Palo Alto, CA, USA).
The validated libraries were used for sequencing on an Illumina MiSeq
platform (BGI, Shenzhen, China) following the standard pipelines of
Illumina, generating 2 × 300 bp paired-end reads. α diversity was assessed
by four different parameters: (1) observed species, (2) Chao1 Index, (3)
Shannon Index, and (4) Simpson Index. β diversity was assessed by the
weighted UniFrac distance metric and is reported according to principal
coordinate analysis.
Metagenomic analysis of fecal samples
Total genomic DNA from fecal samples was extracted using the Qiagen
QIAmp Fast DNA Stool Mini Kit (Qiagen, Valencia, CA, USA) coupled with an
initial bead-beating step as previously described [10]. The metagenomic
shotgun sequencing of human fecal samples from the discovery cohort
(350-bp and 150-bp read length paired-end libraries) was performed on
the Illumina platform. Adapter and low-quality reads were removed from
the raw reads, and the remaining reads were ﬁltered for host DNA based
on the human reference genome. Shotgun metagenomic sequencing of
the validation cohort was performed on the BGISEQ- 500 platform using a
single-ended library with a read length of 100 bp. Low-quality reads and
host reads were excluded.
Metabolic proﬁling of samples from clinical subjects and mice
An ultra-performance liquid chromatography coupled to tandem mass
spectrometry (UPLC-MS/MS) system (ACQUITY UPLC-Xevo TQ-S, Waters,
Milford, MA, USA) was used to quantitate all targeted metabolites in this
study. All samples were maintained at −80 °C until processed. Metabo-
lomics analysis was conducted on serum samples and mouse tissue
samples using the Q300 Metabolite Assay Kit [66]. All of the standards of
targeted metabolites were obtained from Sigma-Aldrich (St. Louis, MO,
USA), Steraloids (Newport, RI, USA), and TRC Chemicals (Toronto, ON,
Canada). Mass spectrometry-based quantitative metabolomics refers to
determination of the concentration of a substance in an unknown sample
by comparing the unknown to a set of standard samples of known
concentration (i.e., calibration curve). A gradient elution was employed
with the mobile phase at a ﬂow rate of 0.45 ml/min. The gradient program
was as follows (B=acetonitrile/IPA): 0–1 min (5% B), 1–11 min (5–78% B),
11–13.5 min (78–95% B), 13.5–14 min (95–100% B), 14–16 min (100% B),
16–16.1 min (100–5% B) and 16.1–18 min (5% B). The column was
maintained at 45 °C, and the injection volume for all samples was 5 μL.
The mass spectrometer operated in negative ion mode with a capillary
voltage of 1.2 kV. The source temperature was set at 150 °C, and the
desolvation gas temperature was 550 °C. Data were collected using
multiple reaction monitoring (MRM), with cone voltage and collision
energy optimized using the QuanOptimize application manager (Waters).
Immunohistochemistry
We determined the number of selected brain sections in the hypothalamus
that expressed Fos after tributyrin administration and analyzed the images
according to previous studies [15]. Brieﬂy, the brains were coronally
sectioned at 30 μm using a sliding microtome. The co-expression of orexin
A and Fos was determined by ﬂuorescent immunohistochemistry. Primary
antibodies were rabbit anti-Fos antibody (1:800, catalog no. 2250S, Cell
Signaling Technology) and mouse anti-orexin A antibody (1:1000, catalog
no. sc80263, Santa Cruz Biotechnology). Secondary antibodies were Alexa
Fluor 488-labeled goat anti-rabbit antibody and Alexa Fluor 594-labeled
goat anti-mouse antibody (both 1:1000 dilution). The co-expression of
MCH and Fos was determined by ﬂuorescent immunohistochemistry.
Primary antibodies were mouse anti-Fos antibody (1:1000, catalog no.
302667, Abcam)
and
rabbit
anti-MCH antibody
(1:50,
catalog
no.
HPA061884, Sigma). Secondary antibodies were Alexa Fluor 488-labeled
goat anti-rabbit antibody and Alexa Fluor 594-labeled goat anti-mouse
antibody (both 1:1000 dilution, catalog no. A32790/A32744, Life Technol-
ogies). Fluorescent imaging and data acquisition were performed on an
Olympus BX61VS ﬂuorescence microscope with a 20× objective lens. We
performed cell quantiﬁcation based on previous reports in a blinded
fashion [67], in which we selected at least 3 sections from each brain
region for each mouse and averaged cell numbers on either side of the
speciﬁc brain region to be the positive immunoreactive cell number for
each mouse. An investigator who was blinded to the experimental
conditions performed the image analyses. Contrast and brightness were
linearly adjusted using ImageJ software (National Institutes of Health,
Bethesda, MD, USA) uniformly across all images within the dataset.
Behavioral tests
Elevated plus maze.
Detailed behavioral test methods were described in
our previous studies [68]. The elevated plus maze consisted of four arms in
a plus conﬁguration. The apparatus was elevated 40 cm above the ﬂoor.
The two open arms were 35 cm long and 5 cm wide. The two closed arms
were 35 cm long and 5 cm wide with 15 cm high walls. Each mouse was
placed in the central zone of the elevated plus maze with its head facing
an open arm. The mice were allowed to freely explore the elevated plus
maze for 5 min under dim illumination. The arena was cleaned with 70%
ethanol between each test. The entire test was recording by an infrared
camera. The number of entries into and time (in seconds) spent on the
open arms were recorded by EthoVision XT Software. The number of
entries into and time (in seconds) spent on the open arms were recorded.
Open ﬁeld test.
The open ﬁeld test apparatus consisted of a 45 cm
length × 45 cm width × 50 cm height square arena that was virtually
divided into 25 equal squares on the ﬂoor of the arena. Each individual
rat was placed in the center of the arena and allowed to freely explore it
for 5 min. The number of crossings (i.e., entering the adjacent square with
all four paws) was recorded as locomotor activity. All of the behavioral test
sessions were videotaped and quantiﬁed by a computerized video tracking
system (EthoVision XT).
Sodium butyrate administration
To test effects of sodium butyrate on behavioral phenotypes, sodium
butyrate (Sigma-Aldrich) was administered ad libitum in drinking water at a
ﬁnal concentration of 40 mM starting 2 weeks after FMT. The drinking
solution was renewed every 2 days. The same doses of sodium butyrate
were used across the previous studies [69].
Tributyrin and valeric acid administration
For tributyrin administration, the mice were habituated to the gavage
procedure by administering 0.3 ml of water for at least 3 days, 10 min
before dark onset. After the habituation period, 0.3 ml of saline or
tributyrin (Millipore Sigma) was administered [43]. Valeric acid (Millipore
Sigma) was administered in the same manner as tributyrin, with the
Z. Wang et al.
13
Molecular Psychiatry
dosage referenced from previous literature [70]. After gavage, the mice
were connected to the EEG/EMG recording system and recorded
continuously for 10 h.
Chemogenetic manipulations
For the chemogenetic experiments, recorded mice were habituated to
experimenter handling for 10-15 min each day for at least 3 consecutive
days. After tributyrin administration, saline or Clozapine-N-oxide (catalog
no. HY-17366) (1 mg/kg) was injected intraperitoneally in random order in
mice that expressed hM3Dq in the target brain regions.
Quantiﬁcation and statistical analysis
Statistical analysis was conducted using SPSS 26.0 software (IBM SPSS,
Chicago, IL, USA). The data are expressed as the mean ± SEM for each
experimental group. The sample distribution was determined using a
Kolmogorov-Smirnov normality test. Statistical signiﬁcance was deter-
mined by Student’s t-test or two-way ANOVA followed by the Sidak post
hoc test. Non-normally distributed data were compared using the Mann-
Whitney U test. Categorical variables were compared between groups
using the χ2 test. Correlations between the abundance of butyrate
producer species and sleep parameters were determined using Spear-
man’s correlation analysis. Values of p < 0.05 were considered statistically
signiﬁcant.
DATA AVAILABILITY
The data that support the ﬁndings of this study are available from the corresponding
author upon reasonable request.
